<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Dimensions</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> Dimensions</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">An introduction to Dimensions, the services we provide for people with a learning disability and autism and the commitments to the people we support.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The Essex Housing Brokerage Service is a project we have been working on for two years. We show how it can be used to change the way landlords view prospective tenants in receipt of benefits and increase the choice and control for people with a learning disability and people with autism.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The implications of the changes for private landlords and social landlords, is likely to mean people with a learning disability have less choice over where they live. Private landlords will be less inclined to rent to people in receipt of benefits and the demand for social housing won’t be met.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">People with a learning disability or autism will have less choice and control over where they live and who they live with. We believe this is not acceptable.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Dimensions</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Dimensions is a leading provider of services for people with learning disabilities and people with autism. A not-for-profit organisation, it supports around 3,000 people and their families throughout England and Wales, enabling people to live a full life </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">in the community and make their own choices and decisions. It provides a wide range of services, including individualised support for people living in their own homes or in shared housing; a team of support advisors who specialise in person-centred plannin</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">g; and specialist behaviour support which focuses on reducing challenging behaviour. Dimensions aim is to deliver personalised support that improves quality of life, keeps people safe, and helps them to become valued members of their community. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">imension</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s’ </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">housing offer covers supported living, group living, registered care homes and tenancies. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Supported living services provide</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> a range of options from 24 hour support to a few hours a week. Group living enables a small group of people, usually two or three, to share a house or flat. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Dimensions runs over 89</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> registered care homes which provide support for people with complex or hig</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">h support needs. In addition, Dimensions has more than 600 tenants. Dimensions </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">oversee</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the management of their home and carry out maintenance</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, whilst other providers support them</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">People with learning disabilities and with autism who</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> we support have told us that it is important for them to have opportunities f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">or greater independence.  Dimensions’ Social Care Charter, written by people we support, recognises that greater independence is ensuring “appropriate housing is available with a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> range of occupancy, tenancy and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ownership options.”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The Charter also shows that people we support want to have choice and control over their relationships, and this includes choosing their home and who they live with. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The coalition government has comm</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">itted to the priorities set out in Valuing People Now, published by the previous administration in 2009, which states one of the overall policy objectives as “All people with a learning disability and their families have the opportunity to make an informed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> choice about where, and with whom, they live.”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that the policy changes taking place with the introduction of Universal Credit, are affecting the rights of the people we support to live in a home they choose, in an area they choose, with people they choose. It’s vital that people </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">with l</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">earning disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> have this control over their life. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Innovative responses to the changes taking place in housing support</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">For the last two</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> years Dimensions have been working with Essex County Council to participate </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">in the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> National Housing and Inclusio</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">n Project being run by the NDTi and the Department of Health.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The scheme piloted the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Housing Brokerage Service and appointed a Housing Broker</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, whose role is to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">support people with learning disabilities to access a range of housing options and increase the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> number of people moving into independent living. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The key aims of the Essex </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Housing Brokerage</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> Service are:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">To pilot a Housing Brokerage demonstration project for people with learning disabilities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">To provide a person-centred approach and an outcome focu</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">sed service to individuals, supporting them and their families to access housing options and help them move onto more independent living. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">To provide the necessary support and advice to enable people to make an informed choice about their living arrangemen</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ts and give them the same rights and responsibilities as other citizens.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The Essex Housing Brokerage Service has been evaluated by the NDTi </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">and deemed </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> a success.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">“I</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">t seems clear that this way of working has real potential for more groups of people in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Essex and offers a model for other parts of the country. The early aims for the EHBS were met and exceeded in an impressive way. It highlights the fact it is of great importance to have someone at the centre of a complex and shifting process particularly i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">f you want to ensure that it remains person-centred.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The evaluation also found that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">was a very cost-effective way of working as it prevented people from returning to expensive services through lack of choice</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. It</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> showed people with learning disabilities can live in a wide range of housing and support settings. “The way of working has great potential for the future – it offers a practical way of delivering personalised solutions in a cost effective way.”</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Based on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the positive outcomes of the project, Essex County Council has agreed to continue fund</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the service and has successfully launched a second project in partnership with Dimensions supporting people with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">physical </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">sensory </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">impairment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We draw on the les</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">sons we have learnt and the barriers faced, through our experience of developing the Essex Housing Brokerage Service in our submission, as well as the experience we offer as providers of support for people with a learning disability and autism.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The impli</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">cations of the changes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> for:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Private landlords</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Private landlords already </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">harge rents in excess of the Local Housing Allowance for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">reasonable accommodation. This </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">makes renting from a private landlord, for</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">disabled </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, an </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">unaffordable</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> option </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">and limits </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the choice they have when choosing a new home.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">aim </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to meet the needs of people we support, and on the introduction of the benefit cap, we believe that private landlords will become even more risk averse. There is already evidence to show that private l</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">andlords don’t consider people on benefits for their empty homes: “one in four private landlords report that they have already begun to look at ways to reduce the number of LHA tenants in their portfolios, and a higher proportion (32%) will do so when capp</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ing affects their lettings.  Half of the landlords surveyed claim the will be less likely to accommodate LHA claimants as tenants in the future.” </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We have been working hard with our housing brokers to try and break the stigma for private landlords to let</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> their homes to people on benefits. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">“By having an in depth understanding of the housing provision available across the county and developing relationships with both social and private landlords</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> choices have been made.”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Social Landlords </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Social landlords </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">have a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">good </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">track record in meeting the needs of the most vulnerable. However, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">insufficient grants mean</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> that waiting lists are long, and growing. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">People with learning disabilities and autism</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> must compete with the rest of the population for the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">scarce resou</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">rce of housing. This is making the attainment of a home for this vulnerable group even more difficult.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The numbers of people with learning disabilities and autism requiring accommodation is growing at the same time that grants are falling, costs are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">rising and long-stay hospitals are closing in favour of supported living</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> or group living</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, with little</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> suitable </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> housing being provided or available to meet the increasing need.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local authorities and discretionary housing payments</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">iscretionary Housing </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Payments are</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> being used for a variety of ways to assist tenants who in some cases have had thei</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">r h</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ousing benefit reduced. However this is only a temporary measure and does not offer a long term solution to meeting the housing needs of many who need to call</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> on this payment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We believe that consideration should be given to these monies to meet the gap in exempt rents that local authoriti</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">es must subsidise and/or use discretionary housing payments</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> to fund deposits and agents fees to private landlords. More and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> more tenants are claiming exempt rents on homes that are meeting their needs that are not met by the private sector or social landlords.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Claimants and those in supported accommodation. </span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There are a number of people we support and would like to have supp</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">orted who live in supported </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">accommodation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">and other housing. Many are in Registered Provider accommodation, but more are having to turn to the private rented sector for a number of reasons: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">A lack of suitable housing from Registered Providers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">A lack of s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">uitable housing from local authorities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The poor level of priority, if any, on choice based letting systems, as nearly all the people we support are not homeless or being threatened with homelessness.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In the private rented sector there are the following is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">sues: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">LHA rates do not offer, for many of the people we support, the opportunity to accept suitable accommodation as housing benefit will not fund the rent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Many landlords will not let directly to people on benefits.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">If 3 or more people wish to share, as</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> is the case with ma</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ny of the people we support, Houses in Multiple Occupation (HMO)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> regulations become enforceable and private landlords are not prepared to either fund or agree to fire alarms and fire doors to be fitted to their homes.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Another issue fac</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ing people we support is the ability of tenants to choose if they wish to have rents paid directly to landlords. Whilst we make every effort to support our clients, there are a number who </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">may </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">receive their rent and NOT pay it to their landlord</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">his then c</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">reates hardship at a later date as the tenant will need to pay their arrears in addition to rent and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">/</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> or end up in court, possibly losing their tenancy and having court costs to pay as well. We acknowledge that a landlord can request rent payments to be ma</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">de direct, but an application can only be made once arrears have accrued to 8 weeks. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The National Housing Federation published a rep</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ort in October 2012, in which it breaks</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> down social tenants into groups</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> according to their ability to cope financially with the changes being made with Universal Credit. 29% of social tenants were classed as ‘troubled reform resistant strugglers’</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the least likely group to cope. Of this 29%, 21% had someone with a learning di</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">sability in the household. Nearly all this group felt “that they would have difficulty in prioritising rent within their budgets, while half are not confident that they could keep up rental payments.”</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> We are concerned that with the choice to have the rent</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> paid directly to the landlord taken away from them, many of the people we support, will find themselves in this position.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Where we find a landlord willing to let to people we support through Dime</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">nsions, Dimensions often ha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> to lease the home and sublet, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">always claiming exempt rents. This increases the housing benefit payable as Dimensions must cover </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">costs</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. The advantage is that the disabled person is able to live in a home of their choice.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">When discussing the proposal to claim an exempt rent with loc</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">al authority staff, it is very difficult to find staff, who are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">well-</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">versed in the regulations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.  S</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ome local authorities refuse to consider the proposed rent and Dimensions being </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the housing and support provider, thus denying the person we support the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">opportunity </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to live in their own home and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> with the people they choose.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Our recommendations</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Private landlords need to be offered some certainty that those on benefits will pay their rents and direct paym</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ents is one such encouragement</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">he rights of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">tenants, particularly those regarded as vulnerable</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> must also be a priority. We believe that tenants should continue to choose if they wish to have their housing costs paid directly to landlords, to avoid unnecessary arrears of rent and court fees and more</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> important</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ly possibly losing their home.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We recommend there be a review of local housing allowance rates to make them more affordable and fair.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We believe that Social landlords need more grants to make available housing that is suitable for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">people with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">learning disabilities and autism,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and which enable Registered Providers to be able to let at social housing rents.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We believe that consideration should be given to these monies to meet the gap in exempt rents that local authorities must subsidise and/or u</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">se discretionary housing payments to fund deposits and agents fees to private landlords. More and more tenants are claiming exempt rents on homes that are meeting their needs that are not met by the private sector or social landlords.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We feel there is a n</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">eed to simplify the definition of supported housing and for Local Authority’s worried about their financial responsibility as they only receive 60% of the rent paid, to be addressed.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Dimensions, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Making it personal: Social Care Charter </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">(2012) available at </span><a href="http://www.dimensions-uk.org/get-involved/our-social-care-charter/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.dimensions-uk.org/get-involved/our-social-care-charter/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> HM Government, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Valuing People Now </span><span st